[LOC United States] ( [LOC US] ) ; [LOC United Kingdom] ( GB ) ; [LOC Zimbabwe] ( ZW ) ; [LOC China] ( [ORG CN] ) 
International ; weapons ; politics 
On 081031 some [LOC United Nation] 's General Assembly 's member nations voted to move ahead with creating an unprecedented treaty regulating the global arms trade despite [LOC United States] opposition . 
[LOC Britain] and 6 other nations supporting an unprecedented treaty regulating the global arms trade won an overwhelming endorsement from the [ORG United Nations General Assembly] on 081031 to move forward with the creation of the treaty regulating the global arms trade despite opposition from the [LOC United States] . 
147 of the [ORG United Nations] 's 192 member nations voted on 081031 to move ahead with crafting the proposed arms trade treaty . 
Most of the nations that did not vote to move ahead with crafting the proposed arms trade treat abstained from 081031 vote . 
[LOC China] abstained from the 081031 vote . 
Only the [LOC United States] and [LOC Zimbabwe] voted against moving ahead with the treaty regulating the global arms trade . 
The [LOC United States] and [LOC Zimbabwe] were bitter opponents in 080700 concerning the [ORG United States] -proposed sanctions on [LOC Zimbabwe] 's leaders that were vetoed by [LOC Russia] and [LOC China] . 
Proponents of the treaty regulating the global arms trade stated that they hope to craft and adopt a treaty within 3 to 5 years with the aim of imposing controls on an international arms trade that contributes to the killing of more than 1000 people a day . 
[LOC Great Britain] , [LOC Japan] , [LOC Australia] , [LOC Argentina] , [LOC Costa Rica] , [LOC Kenya] and [LOC Finland] have been leading proponents of the treaty regulating the global arms trade . 
[LOC Great Britain] is a 3 billion [LOC United States] dollar per year arms exporter . 
The treaty regulating the global arms trade would apply only to arms sales among nations and not commercial sales involving individuals . 
Decisions would require a simple majority . 
[PER John Duncan] stated that the treaty regulating the global arms trade has to be as universal as possible and that some the countries are arms manufacturers and that all nations are arms suppliers at one stage or another . 
[PER John Duncan] stated that it is by closing loopholes that nations can stop arms distribution into the hands of criminals and terrorists . 
[PER John Duncan] is [LOC Great Britain] 's ambassador for multilateral arms control and disarmament . 
The [LOC United States] favors language contained in some of the negotiating documents about treaty regulating the global arms trade that require consensus decisions that essentially give the [LOC United States] and other nations veto power . 
The [LOC United States] diplomat [PER Christina Rocca] stated that the only way to achieve a balanced and effective international mechanism for controlling trade in conventional arms is to proceed on a consensus basis . 
[PER Christina Rocca] made this statement to other nations assembled for the vote on moving ahead with the treaty regulating the global arms trade . 
In 061200 the [LOC United States] cast the sole dissenting vote when 153 nations voted in support of considering the creation of a treaty regulating the global arms trade . 
The 061200 vote set in motion the process of considering an arms trade treaty . 
That process included meetings from 071031 to 081031 among a group of experts that recommended items for consideration that included the consensus language . 
The 081031 vote will move forward arms trade treaty discussions toward the specifics of the possible language of the arms trade treaty . 
[PER Christina Rocca] stated that the [LOC United States] supports the goal of promoting responsibility in arms transfers and reducing the destabilizing trade in illicit arms . 
[PER Christina Rocca] stated that the [LOC United States] does not believe a global arms trade treaty would accomplish the promotion of responsibility in arms transfers and the reduction of the destabilizing trade in illicit arms . 
[PER Christina Rocca] stated that the only way to convince all major arms exporting countries to sign on to the arms trade treaty would be to weaken the arms trade treaty provisions and a weak arms trade treaty would legitimize an international standard based on a lowest common denominator that would not address the problem of illicit and irresponsible arms transfers . 
