2008-04-08 
[LOC China] ( [ORG CN] ) 
Business ; technology ; economy 
The the [ORG Ministry of Economic Affairs] ( moea ) approved lingsen precision industries , King yuan electronics , [ORG IC Assembly] company [ORG Sigurd Corp.] and [MISC Siliconware] precision industries for [MISC Chinese] investment . 
On 8 April 2008 the [ORG Ministry of Economic Affairs] ( moea ) announced approval for 4 [MISC Chinese] investment proposals from [MISC Chinese] manufacturers . 
Lingsen precision industries , King yuan electronics , [ORG IC Assembly] company [ORG Sigurd Corp.] and [MISC Siliconware] precision industries were approved for investment and will invest in integrated circuit packaging ( [ORG ICP] ) and testing . 
The companies will invest 10 million [LOC US] dollars , 20 million [LOC US] dollars , 6.7 million [LOC US] dollars , and 50 million [LOC US] dollars respectively . 
The proposals have a total investment amount of 86.7 million [LOC US] dollars ( 2.64 billion [LOC NT] dollars ) . 
The moea determined in a meeting on 8 April 2008 that the investment proposals met the clauses in the [LOC China] Investment procedure issued by the ministry 's [ORG Investment Commission] . 
[ORG The Investment Commission] 's Executive Secretary [PER Fan Liang-Tung] stated the investment procedure aims to ensure [LOC Taiwan] 's investments in [LOC China] will not harm [LOC Taiwan] 's industries and economy such as by leaking key technologies to the mainland . 
Under the procedure investment plans require approval from the moea if the plans involve a single investment that exceeds 100 million [LOC US] dollars , the company 's total investment in [LOC China] reaches 200 million [LOC US] dollars , or the investment could transfer core local industries' technologies to [LOC China] . 
Fan stated core industries mainly involve the manufacturing of 8-inch wafers and 4-inch TFT panels as well as [ORG IC] packaging . 
After the meeting on 8 April 2008 the [ORG Commission] requires written documents to further assess the plans which contain each company 's commitment on the terms of investment including the financial plan , information on any technology transfers and the company 's domestic investment as well as employment information . 
Fan stated the [ORG Commission] is primarily concerned with the term of future investment in [LOC Taiwan] . 
Fan stated lingsen precision industries , King yuan electronics , [ORG IC Assembly] company [ORG Sigurd Corp.] and [MISC Siliconware] precision industries have made commitments to return capital to [LOC Taiwan] in the amounts of 2 billion [LOC NT] dollars , 19.2 billion [LOC NT] dollars , 3 billion [LOC NT] dollars and 23 billion [LOC NT] dollars respectively by 2011 . 
Fan stated the [ORG Commission] will ensure the commitments are upheld once the investments are under way . 
Fan stated the procedure would push [MISC Chinese] investment from [LOC Taiwan] to focus on down scale manufacturers rather than technology-concentrated makers in a bid to keep high-end technologies in [LOC Taiwan] . 
Fan stated the [ORG Commission] will hold a 2nd round of meetings to decide if the proposals will take effect and that the final decision will be made by 30 April 2008 . 
1995-12-18 
[LOC Germany] ( [LOC DE] ) 
International ; weapons ; war and conflict 
The process to try to control and reduce arms in the embattled [LOC Balkans] was formally launched in [LOC Bonn] , [LOC Germany] , when foreign ministers , ambassadors and representatives of international organizations and observer nations met to discuss what form further talks should take . 
The long process to try to control and reduce arms in the embattled [LOC Balkans] was formally launched on 951218 in [LOC Bonn] , [LOC Germany] . 
Foreign ministers , ambassadors and representatives of international organizations and observer nations met in [LOC Bonn] to discuss what form further talks should take . 
There are huge obstacles to achieving peace and cooperation among combatants in the former [LOC Yugoslavia] . 
[MISC German] Foreign Minister [PER Klaus Kinkel] said in opening remarks at the one-day meeting that there can be no peace in the former [LOC Yugoslavia] if some parties to the conflict remain heavily armed and others try to catch up . 
The [MISC Croation] delegation threatened to pull out of arms-reduction negotiations if certain demands were not met in the nearest future . 
Delegates from other countries called on [LOC Croatia] , [LOC Bosnia-Herzegovina] and [LOC Serbia] to set aside their grievances and learn to compromise . 
[MISC Croatian] Foreign Minister [PER Mate Granic] complained that a part of [MISC Croatian] territory is under occupation and time is running out . 
[PER Granic] said in reference to disputed lands on the [MISC Croatian] - [MISC Serbian] border that the peaceful re-integration of [LOC Eastern] Slavonia is the key to the lasting stability in the region and that everyone faces the danger of another round of hostilities and the destabilization of the whole region and highly unpredictable consequences for [LOC Bosnia-Herzegovina] without it . 
Conference participants said Foreign Minister [PER Milan Milutinovic] from [LOC Serbia] scolded his [MISC Croatian] counterpart for grandstanding . 
Then [MISC Milutinovic] made a threat to pull out of arms-control negotiations . 
Milutinovic noted the [MISC Serbian] Government has been suspended since 920000 from the [ORG Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe] and said that unless full membership were restored [LOC Yugoslavia] will be prevented from cooperating despite its readiness to do so . 
The [ORG OSCE] is to oversee the next round of [LOC Balkan] arms-reduction talks . 
[PER Michael Williams] is a senior fellow at the [ORG International Institute for Strategic Studies] in [LOC London] and formerly the [ORG United Nations'] senior spokesman for [LOC Croatia] and called the early threats from [LOC Croatia] and [LOC Serbia] a worrying development and an ominous development . 
[ORG Williams] said it was really not clear that the parties are willing to engage in any arms control in a meaningful way . 
This corresponds to a fear expressed by some delegates to the 951218 [LOC Bonn] meeting that the yugolav parties do not want to negotiate away the ability to use violence or a threat of violence to seize territory . 
[MISC Greek] Foreign Minister [PER karelos Papoulias] observed of the [LOC Balkan] belligerents that during talk in the plenary session one realizes that this is still the way they are thinking . 
[PER Papoulias] said the [MISC Greek] government is not as optimistic as other [MISC European] partners and that just because there is a Conference doesn't mean there is friendship between the people of the former [LOC Yugoslavia] . 
The 951218 talks were organized to fulfill the combatants' pledge made in [LOC Dayton] , [LOC Ohio] , to begin talks to enhance mutual confidence and reduce the risk of conflict within 7 days of the [ORG Peace Accord] 's formal signing . 
The agenda on 951218 was limited to set the formal process for coming weeks . 
The [MISC German] [ORG Foreign Ministry] said in a statement that this was so as to clear the way for speedy negotiation of the substantive questions . 
[LOC Croatia] , [LOC Bosnia-Herzegovina] and [LOC Serbia] are the nations that signed the [LOC Dayton] accord and are supposed to report how many tanks and armored vehicles , heavy artillery pieces , combat aircraft and attack helicopters they possess in the next phase . 
This data will be used to establish baselines from which weapons ceilings can be agreed on . 
[LOC Croatia] , [LOC Bosnia-Herzegovina] and [LOC Serbia] have promised to accept a set of automatic limits if agreement on such ceilings cannot be reached in 180 days . 
[PER Kinkel] said that on 951218 delegates had been unable to fix a date for the next round of talks but said the next talks would be 960104 or 960107 in [LOC Vienna] . 
[PER Kinkel] said minor problems not substantive discord kept delegates from choosing a firm date . 
1999-06-30 
[LOC India] ( IN ) ; [LOC Korea] , [ORG Democratic People 's Republic of] ( [ORG KP] ) 
International ; technology ; weapons ; government 
[MISC Indian] officials seize missile assembly line from the [MISC North Korean] vessel the kuwolsan on 30 June 1999 . 
The discovery heightens suspicions of [MISC North Korean] weapons proliferation . 
On 30 June 1999 [MISC Indian] customs agents in the northwestern port city of [LOC Kandla] boarded the [MISC North Korean] freighter kuwolsan . 
Following a melee with the crew of the kuwolsan , customs agents discovered an assembly line for ballistic missiles . 
[LOC U.S.] intelligence officials stated [MISC Libyan] government was the intended recipient of the cargo . 
The kuwolsan departed [LOC North Korea] 's [LOC Nampo] harbor on 10 April 1999 . 
Records show that on 20 April 1999 the kuwolsan made detours to 2 [MISC Thai] ports to pick up 14000 tons of sugar for resale along the way to the kuwolsan 's destination . 
The kuwolsan switched course in order to sell the sugar to an [MISC Indian] company after a deal to sell the sugar to [MISC Algerians] failed . 
An [MISC Indian] investigator stated that the crew of the kuwolsan should not have picked up extra cargo at several ports when carrying 200 tons of sensitive equipment and that such activity was crazy . 
[MISC Indian] customs officials were tipped off to possible contraband on the kuwolsan while the kuwolsan was en route to [LOC Kandla] . 
The kuwolsan was rumored to be carrying arms or ammunition possibly intended for [LOC Pakistan] . 
[MISC Indian] port officials were waiting when the kuwolsan arrived in [LOC Kandla] on 25 June 1999 . 
Irregularities in the kuwolsan 's papers were apparent within the first few hours of investigation . 
[MISC Indian] officials learned that the company in [LOC Malta] listed as the intended recipient of the cargo was fictitious . 
[MISC Indian] officials questioned why anyone in [LOC Malta] would choose to buy water refining equipment from [LOC North Korea] when [LOC Malta] is a short flight from [LOC Europe] . 
[MISC Indian] customs agents questioned the captain of the kuwolsan [PER Tae Min Hun] . 
[PER Tae] blocked every request and threatened international reprisals if [MISC Indian] officials did not allow [PER Tae] to leave [LOC Kandla] . 
On 30 June 1999 customs officials demanded to search the kuwolsan 's cargo boxes and [PER Tae] stated that the kuwolsan had received a telex from [MISC North Korean] officials . 
Tae received instructions from officials in [LOC Pyongyang] to allow no one to open the cargo boxes at all costs . 
The official [MISC Indian] after-action report stated [PER Tae] would not open any more boxes as per the telex . 
The report stated the crew members shouted at and abused the customs officers . 
According to witness accounts and video footage of the encounter , tae and the crew of the kuwolsan barricaded the doors of the kuwolsan with the crews' bodies . 
An [MISC Indian] official who was present on the kuwolsan and who spoke on the condition of anonymity stated the situation became physical and there were fisticuffs . 
The official stated the crew began closing the hatches to the cargo hold with the customs inspectors still inside . 
On 1 July 1999 armed troops and a group of government weapons experts aided customs officials and gained forcible entry onto the kuwolsan . 
A few crates among the kuwolsan 's cargo contained equipment that could be used in a water treatment plant . 
Inspectors found pumps , nozzles and a few valves . 
The cargo boxes were labeled as water refinement equipment . 
Documents from the investigation contain a partial list of the contents of most of the cargo crates which included -- 
Components for missile subassembly . 
[ORG Machine Tools] for setting up a fabrication facility . 
Instrumentation for evaluating the performance of a full missile system . 
Equipment for calibrating missile components . 
Rocket nose cones , stacks of metal pipe and heavy-duty presses used for milling high-grade steel . 
A Plate-bending machine capable of rolling thick metal sheets , toroidal air bottles used to guide warheads after separation from a missile , and [PER Theodolites] that measure missile trajectories . 
Several boxes of engineering drawings , blueprints , notebooks , textbooks and reports . 
Personal items presumably intended for [MISC North Korean] workers , including cookbooks in [MISC Korean] , [MISC Korean] spices , pickles and acupuncture sets . 
An [MISC Indian] government official familiar with the kuwolsan discovery stated that in the past officials had seen missiles or engine parts , but here was an entire assembly line for missiles offered for sale . 
The official stated that this was a complete technology transfer . 
A technical committee of [MISC Indian] missile experts stated that the equipment was unimpeachable and irrefutable evidence of a plan to transfer not just missiles but missile-making capability . 
The technical panel wrote in a report that the cargo points to only one end-use , namely the assembling of missiles and manufacture of the parts and subassemblies of surface to surface missiles . 
Investigators searched the blueprints that were kept inside numbered plastic jackets and wrapped in brown paper . 
Some of the packets were labeled in [MISC English] as Scud B or Scud [PER C. Nearly] all of the drawings showed rockets or sections of rockets with notes and mathematical formulas handwritten in [MISC Korean] . 
[MISC Native Korean] speakers assisted in translation but the documents contained technical code invented by [MISC North Korean] scientists to replace scientific terms in [MISC Russian] or [MISC Chinese] . 
The investigation ultimately yielded information about [LOC North Korea] 's weapons program which [MISC Indian] authorities shared with ally Governments . 
The Scud B and Scud C designs found on the kuwolsan were from older [MISC North Korean] missile programs which were derived from [LOC Soviet] missile designs of the 1950s . 
One [MISC Indian] government official who studied the blueprints stated the science was old and dated but still functional . 
Retired director of the [ORG State Department 's Office] on strategic , proliferation and military issues in the [ORG Bureau of Intelligence and Research] [PER Greg Thielmann] stated the [ORG CIA] utilized the blueprints to make full mock-ups of missiles complete with decals . 
The blueprints included information pertaining to the inner workings of [LOC North Korea] 's missile industry which has been the focus of contention between the [LOC United States] and [LOC North Korea] since the 1980s . 
The cargo on the kuwolsan did not include everything needed for missile production which raises the possibility that there may have been earlier and possible later shipments . 
Missile expert and senior analyst at the [ORG Center for Nonproliferation Studies] [PER Timothy V. McCarthy] examined some of the blueprints and other evidence and stated this was a slice in time of a technology transfer from [LOC North Korea] to [LOC Libya] . 
[PER McCarthy] stated the intelligence find helps [LOC U.S.] officials learn how [MISC North Korean] missile scientists learn . 
[PER McCarthy] stated the information gives [LOC U.S.] officials an idea of how capable [MISC North Korean] scientists are of progressing to more advanced missiles and gives [LOC U.S.] officials insight into the aspect of proliferation when one country 's officials attempt to transfer technology to another country 's officials . 
[PER McCarthy] stated no one can stop [MISC Libyan] scientists once the scientists are capable of making missiles . 
The kuwolsan and the crew were unaccounted for after [MISC Indian] officials released the kuwolsan in 2000 . 
Shipping experts at [LOC Lloyd 's] maritime division in [LOC London] stated the kuwolsan 's name was changed in the summer of 2000 to [ORG Sun] grisan 9 . 
As of the week of 3 August 2003 the sun grisan 9 was still in service and was last reported headed to the [MISC Somalian] capital of [LOC Mogadishu] . 
The nature of the [ORG Sun grisan] 9 's cargo was unknown . 
As of 14 August 2003 the evidence from the kuwolsan is secured in a military warehouse in [LOC New Delhi] . 
As stated in court documents and interviews with officials in the [LOC United States] and [LOC India] the kuwolsan incident has reinforced a view of [LOC North Korea] as the world 's most dangerous source of weapons proliferation . 
In 1999 [MISC North Korean] leader [PER Kim Jong Il] expelled [ORG U.N.] inspectors , abandoned the [MISC Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty] and declared plans to build an atomic weapon . 
[LOC U.S.] intelligence officials stated that [MISC North Korean] officials are continuing global trade in technology for weapons of mass destruction including instructions for making advanced missiles . 
Successive [LOC U.S.] administrations have condemned [LOC North Korea] 's missile sales to such countries as [LOC Iran] and [LOC Syria] . 
On 31 August 1998 [MISC North Korean] officials launched a 3-stage missile which heightened fears of advanced [MISC North Korean] designs capable of reaching the [LOC U.S.] mainland . 
The first stage splashed down in the [LOC Sea] of [LOC Japan] , the second stage crossed the main island of [LOC Japan] and the third broke up and traveled 3450 miles downrange and fell into the [LOC Pacific Ocean] . 
The missile test fueled work on a [LOC U.S.] missile defense shield . 
[MISC North Korean] officials have defended the right to sell weapons and have stated that [MISC North Korean] officials are not bound by international treaties restricting such trade . 
[MISC North Korean] officials have sold missiles and parts to [LOC Yemen] which received 15 Scud missiles after the missiles were briefly intercepted by [LOC U.S.] and [MISC Spanish] naval crews off the [MISC Yemeni] coast in December 1998 . 
[LOC Libya] appears to be the latest beneficiary of [MISC North Korean] weapons . 
Other nations including [LOC Iran] , [LOC Pakistan] and [LOC Syria] are known to have received similar help . 
The kuwolsan cargo attests to the existence of a gray zone composed of a combination of weak States , open borders , lack of controls and a market of buyers and sellers of weapons of mass destruction . 
Small packages are sometimes delivered in the luggage of individual airline passengers such as a [MISC Taiwanese] businessman arrested at [LOC Zurich] 's airport in 2000 with [MISC North Korean] missile parts in a rucksack . 
Larger items are moved in freighters such as the kuwolsan while technical information and designs are accessible via the [MISC Internet] . 
[LOC Korea] specialist with the [ORG Center for Nonproliferation Studies] at the [ORG Monterey Institute of International Studies] in [LOC California] [PER Daniel pinkston] stated that intercepting weapons and equipment is difficult but not impossible but that human exchanges of plans , data , and intellectual property are difficult to intercept . 
